         b'\n\t\t</div>\n\n\t\t<div class="post-385 post type-post status-publ'
         b'ish format-standard hentry category-context category-event category-'
         b'future category-info-overload category-recommendations category-reco'
         b'mmender-systems category-research" id="post-385">\n\t\t\t<h2>A Pitch'
         b' on Future Recommender Systems</h2>\n\n\t\t\t<div class="entry">\n'
         b'\t\t\t\t<p>Yesterday I attended a workshop that was aimed at fosteri'
         b'ng research collaboration between our department and BSkyB. After a '
         b'short introduction by the head of the department, a number of member'
         b's of staff gave short (10 minute) pitches about their past and curre'
         b'nt research, and areas they are interested in for potential collabor'
         b'ation. The range of work being done in the department is huge- perha'
         b'ps this deserves a post of its own.</p>\n<div id="__ss_790774" st'
         b'yle="width: 425px; text-align: left;"><a style="font:14px Helvetica,'
         b'Arial,Sans-serif;display:block;margin:12px 0 3px 0;text-decoration:u'
         b'nderline;" title="BSkyB - UCL Collaboration Workshop" href="http://w'
         b'ww.slideshare.net/neal.lathia/bskyb-ucl-collaboration-workshop-prese'
         b'ntation?type=powerpoint">BSkyB &#8211; UCL Collaboration Workshop</a'
         b'><object classid="clsid:d27cdb6e-ae6d-11cf-96b8-444553540000" width='
         b'"425" height="355" codebase="http://download.macromedia.com/pub/shoc'
         b'kwave/cabs/flash/swflash.cab#version=6,0,40,0"><param name="allowFul'
         b'lScreen" value="true" /><param name="allowScriptAccess" value="alway'
         b's" /><param name="src" value="http://static.slideshare.net/swf/sspla'
         b'yer2.swf?doc=bskybpresentation-1227711303962160-9&amp;stripped_title'
         b'=bskyb-ucl-collaboration-workshop-presentation" /><embed type="appli'
         b'cation/x-shockwave-flash" width="425" height="355" src="http://stati'
         b'c.slideshare.net/swf/ssplayer2.swf?doc=bskybpresentation-12277113039'
         b'62160-9&amp;stripped_title=bskyb-ucl-collaboration-workshop-presenta'
         b'tion" allowscriptaccess="always" allowfullscreen="true"></embed></ob'
         b'ject></p>\n<div style="font-size: 11px; font-family: tahoma,arial'
         b'; height: 26px; padding-top: 2px;">View SlideShare <a style="text-de'
         b'coration:underline;" title="View BSkyB - UCL Collaboration Workshop '
         b'on SlideShare" href="http://www.slideshare.net/neal.lathia/bskyb-ucl'
         b'-collaboration-workshop-presentation?type=powerpoint">presentation</'
         b'a> or <a style="text-decoration:underline;" href="http://www.slidesh'
         b'are.net/upload?type=powerpoint">Upload</a> your own. (tags: <a style'
         b'="text-decoration:underline;" href="http://slideshare.net/tag/recomm'
         b'ender">recommender</a> <a style="text-decoration:underline;" href="h'
         b'ttp://slideshare.net/tag/systems">systems</a>)</div>\n</div>\n<p><'
         b'span id="more-385"></span>I presented (along with one of my supervis'
         b'ors <a href="http://www.cs.ucl.ac.uk/staff/l.capra/">Licia Capra</a>'
         b') on future recommender systems. Given that I had less than 10 minut'
         b'es to talk on this incredibly broad and interesting subject, there w'
         b'as no way I could say everything I wanted. So I tried to compress my'
         b' ideas into four key points:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><strong>Motivating Rec'
         b'ommender Systems.</strong> This part sounds obvious; I&#8217;ve read'
         b' countless papers that talk about <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/w'
         b'iki/Information_overload">information overload</a>, a term that come'
         b's from a <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Future_Shock">book</a'
         b'> (with other theories of arguable value?). However, as the interest'
         b' in recommender systems grows and the research fields matures, the m'
         b'otivation itself seems to be shifting: we are leaving behind (tradit'
         b'ional) approaches to search and web interaction and heading toward a'
         b'n age of information <em>personalisation and discovery</em>. I playe'
         b'd on this idea by modifying the google home page (see slide 2 of my '
         b'presentation).</li>\n<li><strong>Born on the Web</strong>. When w'
         b'e think of recommender systems, we think of the web. We think about '
         b'the <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Wisdom_of_Crowds">wisd'
         b'om of the crowds</a>. The typical example thrown around in the pub ('
         b'to non-researchers) is Amazon. To highlight the flood of online syst'
         b'ems, I borrowed a slide from <a href="http://www.iua.upf.es/~ocelma/'
         b'">Oscar Celma</a>&#8216;s music recommendation tutorial. So: what do'
         b'es this mean? Interacting with a recommender system is a lonely expe'
         b'rience; we sit alone in front of a computer screen. We receive recom'
         b'mendations for ourselves, based on our profile. I echoed the &#8220;'
         b'users who have been like-minded in the past will be like-minded in t'
         b'he future&#8230;&#8221; assumption that we build these systems on. T'
         b'he key is that the data that traditional systems have been handling '
         b'assumes individual profiles, an early warning for my next point:</li'
         b'>\n<li><strong>Future Systems.</strong> Recommender systems centr'
         b'e on music, movies, and (in general) e-commerce items. So which way '
         b'are things moving? Already there is exciting potential for recommend'
         b'ing <a href="http://blog.scrump.com/">people</a>, which moves away f'
         b'rom the traditional way things work. Search engine prototypes are ma'
         b'king it a <a href="http://www.heystaks.com/">social</a> <a href="htt'
         b'p://porqpine.com/">experience</a>. What else? I split this part into'
         b' two halves:\n<ol>\n<li><strong>Leaving the Web Behind</strong>. T'
         b'he age of (information) discovery need not reside only on the web. W'
         b'hat about recommending television (like the <a href="http://www.grav'
         b'ityrd.com/">RecSys Strands Startup Winners</a>, and work being done '
         b'at <a href="http://technocalifornia.blogspot.com/2008/11/recsys-08.h'
         b'tml">Telefonica I+D</a>)? What about discovering content when on the'
         b' move (like work being done by <a href="http://www.cs.ucl.ac.uk/staf'
         b'f/d.quercia/">these</a> <a href="http://www.cs.ucl.ac.uk/staff/l.mcn'
         b'amara/">two</a> guys)? In other words, heads up for ubiquitous recom'
         b'mender systems. We are going to be building systems that mirror the '
         b'interaction that has been happening online. Next thing you know your'
         b' fridge will be recommending what the best dinner you can make is.</'
         b'li>\n<li><strong>Emerging from the Web</strong>. On the other han'
         b'd, a few minutes browsing around show that, rather than building a w'
         b'orld to mirror web interactions, the systems online may move outward'
         b'. Google <a href="http://www.technologyreview.com/blog/editors/22202'
         b'/">plans to take over tv</a>, Telefonica&#8217;s Imagenio <a href="h'
         b'ttp://www.iptv-news.com/content/view/1451/64/">is growing</a>, and <'
         b'a href="http://arstechnica.com/news.ars/post/20080718-major-eu-p2p-r'
         b'esearch-project-hopes-to-kill-traditional-tv.html">p2p will kill tra'
         b'ditional television</a> (note the bias to tv: remember who I was pre'
         b'senting to!)</li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n<li><strong>What does this mean?</'
         b'strong> Well, it means a lot of things. But the point of most intere'
         b'st (to me) is that both the <em>context of</em> recommendation and <'
         b'em>context for</em> recommendation are changing. Context Of? We will'
         b' be in different places, looking for different things, with differen'
         b't people and friends (see a recent tutorial at RecSys by <a href="ht'
         b'tp://ids.csom.umn.edu/faculty/gedas/">Amodavicius</a>). Context for?'
         b' We will be seeking recommendations at different times (and don&#821'
         b'7;t tell me that having a hard disk on your television means you won'
         b'&#8217;t want to see the world cup final live!), we will be seeking '
         b'recommendations for groups (recommend to a family?). We need finer g'
         b'rained models of users, in environments where getting this kind of i'
         b'nformation is more difficult.</li>\n</ol>\n<p>This is just a brain'
         b' dump of what&#8217;s left after my rushed talk. Any thoughts?</'
         b'p>\n\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\n\t\t\t\t<p class="postmetadata alt">\n\t\t'
